story.title: Falco - Episode 3
story.storyDescription: Libby Dixon is missing. Will Agent Falco crack the case?
story.creator: web-uploader
story.prePaywallNotification: Oh no! Agent Falco found Libby Dixon’s broken bracelet at the site of her disappearance. Was Libby abducted after all? Tap back into Hooked to find out.
story.postPaywallNotification: Woah…why did Billy Townsend find a burnt and bloody police uniform? Does it have something to do with the Libby Dixon case? Tap into Hooked to find out 🔥🔪

messages.text: Investigation: Day 3
The following is a voicemail from Agent Falco to Sheriff Simmons, left June 22, 9:18 AM.
Hey, Sheriff, it’s Agent Falco. I missed you at the office this morning and was hoping to get in touch today.
I’d like to interview your son Duke about the Dixon girl.
I think he could be helpful in recreating Libby’s frame of mind prior to her disappearance—
Maybe she confided something in him, since she was going through such a rough time emotionally.
Once I check his alibi for June 18, we can rule him out and move forward with the case.
Okay, please call me back so we can set something up. Thanks. Bye.
The following is a text message conversation between Deputy Decker and Agent Falco, initiated June 22, 12:03 PM.
Good afternoon, Agent Falco. I’m over at the police impound lot checking out Libby’s vehicle, per your request.
Did you find anything?
No more beads, but I’m suspicious of her flat tire.
Search & Rescue didn’t see any glass or nails in the road.
It could have been over-pumped.
It’s been unusually hot out this week. When temps get this hot the air inside the tires expands—
Could be the cause of a blowout.
That’s possible, but the tire looks like it’s been punctured—
Maybe deliberately.
The slit has smooth edges. Not the expectation from a blowout.
And it’s located on the sidewall, the most vulnerable part of the tire.
But if the tire was slashed before Libby entered her vehicle at the motel, she wouldn’t have driven off on a flat, would she?
Not unless the poor girl didn’t notice ’til she hit the road.
I doubt that — the car would feel off. So it stands to reason that, if the tire was punctured willfully…
It must have occurred at the site of Libby’s disappearance.
You think she pulled over, engaged in a struggle, and then her attacker cut the tire?
I wouldn’t rule it out.
It seems a little far-fetched, doesn’t it?
And why would she have pulled over if not for the flat tire?
Do you have an alternate theory, Deputy?
Maybe Libby staged the scene herself.
She left the phone so it couldn’t be tracked.
She pulled over and knifed her tire to make it look like she had a blowout.
Then she broke her bracelet and scattered the beads so we’d think there was a struggle.
But why?
That’s a lot of trouble to go through.
Maybe she needed to escape some kind of abuse…
And she didn’t want her abuser to know she’s still out there.
You’re referring to Duke Simmons, I’m guessing.
But why didn’t she take the fake ID with her?
Maybe she forgot it.
I’ll see if I can get Libby’s medical records from Lynette.
If she was a victim of ongoing abuse, there may be some clues in there—
Even if she didn’t verbalize them.
Like ER visits and broken bones?
Exactly — but she may not have sought treatment for her injuries.
And abuse doesn’t always leave a mark.
It’s a jumping off point, though.
What do you know about her father?
Darrence?
He’s a preacher over at the Baptist church.
He does have a reputation for being pretty strict.
With his daughters?
Yeah, and his parishioners, too.
He takes the Scripture seriously — a real God-fearing man.
It sounds like you have a lot of respect for him.
Yeah, I guess I do.
But I think he needs to loosen up a bit with his kids.
It’s like he’s raising little nuns in a convent or something.
I thought nuns were strictly a Catholic thing.
There’s actually nuns in lots of different religious traditions — Christianity, Buddhism, Hinduism, and so forth.
You seem to know a lot about religion, Deputy.
I read the Bible and attend services when I’m off the job.
At Darrence’s church?
No, I’m Presbyterian, but we do charity work with Darrence’s church sometimes.
Do you think it’s possible that Darrence Dixon has been physically or sexually abusive with his daughters?
I really don’t know.
I can’t say that sexual abuse is absent in the churches…
But Cedar Creek’s never had any reports of things like that.
I do know that Darrence’s eldest daughter, Anna Mae, has had some emotional issues, same as Libby.
Emotional issues?
I heard she went through a bad breakup about two weeks ago.
Okay, with whom?
Jimmy-something.
He’s been in Cedar Creek about two years, I think.
You think?
Yeah, well, my source was all hyped-up on ice cream at the time, talking a mile a minute.
Her mom doesn’t let her have sugar.
Your daughter, I take it?
Yeah. Cate’s thirteen.
I’m guessing you don’t keep her on a tight leash like Darrence does with his daughters.
No, but I don’t see my daughter that often.
I get her every other weekend, if I’m not working.
But when she’s here, it’s all Taylor Swift and America’s Next Top Model. She’s really into that stuff.
Right. Anyway, I’m going to look into Darrence Dixon a bit.
We shouldn’t theorize too much until we get some more information about the tire.
Get an expert down to the impound lot to take a look at it, okay?
We need an official report evaluating the likelihood that the tire was punctured deliberately.
Roger that, boss.
I’m not your boss, Tex.
Talk soon.
The following is a transcript of an interview between Agent Falco and Billy Townsend, recorded June 22, 2:50 PM.
Thanks for coming in today, Mr. Townsend. Can you please state your full name and occupation for the record?
Yeah, uh — Billy Townsend.
I’m an outdoorsman — I own a tackle shop, and I’m the editor of a local fishing magazine called “Creek Bed.”
And what brings you by today?
Well, I was out hiking yesterday and I found something kind of suspicious…
What’s that?
Is that a sheriff’s uniform?
It’s been burned up, ma’am.
And the patch is cut out of the sleeve.
Where’d you find it?
It was poking out of the dirt—
I don’t think it’s routine to burn and bury old police uniforms like this.
No, it’s not protocol.
Let me see the sleeve.
Ain’t that where the patches go?
Yes. They contain the deputy’s identifying information.
Look at the pants.
Right on the knee.
Dark red spots.
Could that be blood?
Possibly. We’ll have to send it to the lab for testing.
Seems really creepy to me…
That’s why I asked to speak to you personally.
What do you mean?
The Sheriff’s Office ‘round here protects their own—
They ain’t gonna look into this if one of them had something to do with it.
How did you know I was here, Billy?
You’re from Nashville, yeah?
I am.
About how many people live in Nashville?
Yeah. And there’s only like 3,000 people in this town.
You’re saying there’s some small town gossip?
Something like that, yeah.
News sure gets around here, doesn’t it?
Yes ma’am — especially when a kid goes missing.
And that’s why you should be careful.
What do you mean?
If you’re gonna look into the Sheriff’s Office ‘cause of this uniform…
You gotta make sure to stay under their radar, so to speak.
Why are you afraid of the Sheriff’s Office, Billy?
I’m not afraid. I just don’t like it when they make things go away.
Make things go away?
Like what?
Like that Duke Simmons, the Sheriff’s boy—
Mary Beth Hutton filed assault charges against him a few years back.
But Duke Simmons doesn’t have a criminal record.
Yeah, because the Big Bad Sheriff scared the girl into recanting.
She ended up telling the police that her broken arm was an accident.
You seem pretty upset about Mary Beth, Billy.
Yeah, well, I’m her uncle.
I should’ve protected the kid, you know.
Can I please speak to her?
Wish you could.
She and her mother were both killed in a car crash last December, God rest their souls.
Oh, I’m sorry to hear that.
She’d just gotten her learner’s permit.
Look, is that all you need from me, Agent Falco?
I’d like to catch me some catfish before we lose the light.
One more question, if you don’t mind. I’m looking for a little more information than you gave earlier—
Exactly where did you find this uniform?
In the woods behind Route 12.
About a mile south of Exit 66.
Okay. That’s about it for now.
Thanks for coming in, Mr. Townsend. I’ll be in touch if I need anything else.
Good to meet you, detective.
You too, sir.
The following is a voicemail from Sheriff Simmons to Agent Falco, left June 22, 4:16 PM.
Yeah, this is Sheriff Simmons. I don’t appreciate you asking about my son Duke—
And I won’t allow you to cast undue suspicion on him with your investigation.
It’s obvious to the entire office that the Dixon girl ran off to be with a boyfriend.
She checked into a smutty motel with a fake ID, she withdrew $200 from her savings account, and she took off after her tire blew.
You’re wasting your time and the time of my deputies on a troubled teen runaway. Ask about my son again, and I’ll be putting a call into your boss.
You need to watch yourself, Agent.
This ain’t how we do things in Cedar Creek.
The following is a communication from “Connor Mason” to Agent Falco on the Facespace messaging app, initiated June 22, 5:43 PM.
Stop looking for Libby Dixon. You aren’t needed in Cedar Creek.
Connor, talk to me—
Who are you?
Do you know where Libby is?
It’s better if she isn’t found.
What do you mean by that?
Is Libby in danger?
No.
Not anymore.
Connor Mason is offline.
